Ledger Module

The sovereign authority layer of Posta.

This module is not logging.

It is not analytics.

It is not projection.

It is constitutional memory.

Everything else in the system is derived state.

The ledger is the source of institutional truth.

Core Guarantees

The ledger guarantees:

Cryptographic immutability

Deterministic ordering

Structural supersession rules

Authority hierarchy enforcement

Replay-safe payload evolution

Cross-tenant isolation

Canonical append-only history

If the database is corrupted, but the ledger remains intact, authority can be reconstructed.

If projections drift, the ledger resolves truth.

Architectural Position

All domain modules commit through:

commitLedgerEvent()

They must NOT call LedgerService directly.

The wrapper enforces:

Zod boundary validation

Structured actor schema

Transaction compatibility

Stable import surface

Centralized evolution

The LedgerService is constitutional core.
The wrapper is the only gateway.

1. Authority Envelope (Versioned Payloads)

File:
authorityEnvelope.ts

Ledger payloads must be wrapped in an authority envelope.

Example:

{
envelopeVersion: 1,
domain: "CASE_LIFECYCLE",
event: "TRANSITION",
data: {...}
}

Why?

Because eventType (enum) classifies.
Envelope version governs schema evolution.

This enables:

Multi-year durability

Backward-compatible replay

Payload shape evolution without DB migration

Future versions must be additive and backward compatible.

Never write raw payload directly again.

2. Authority Hierarchy Policy

File:
authorityHierarchy.policy.ts

Defines derived authority levels:

SYSTEM_AUTOMATED

HUMAN_VERIFIER

HUMAN_ADMIN

EXECUTIVE_OVERRIDE

Supersession rules:

Lower authority cannot supersede higher.

SYSTEM cannot supersede HUMAN.

Equal authority requires escalation.

Authority derivation is currently convention-based:

Prefix rules:

EXEC: → executive override

ADMIN: → admin

default → verifier

No schema changes required.

Authority enforcement happens inside commit() before append.

This is structural governance, not business logic.

3. Canonical Commit Wrapper

File:
commitLedgerEvent.ts

This is the only acceptable entry point for domain modules.

Responsibilities:

Validate input

Enforce structured actor schema

Normalize optional fields

Delegate to LedgerService

Support transaction boundary

Design rule:

No domain module imports LedgerService directly.

This allows:

Future tracing hooks

Metrics injection

Governance instrumentation

Drift prevention

4. LedgerService (Constitutional Core)

File:
ledger.service.ts

This is the immutable authority engine.

It provides:

RSA key management

Canonical hashing

Deterministic serialization

Logical clock sequencing

Supersession validation

Signature generation

Append-only persistence

Cryptographic Model

Each commit generates:

Canonical structured object

Deterministic JSON canonicalization

SHA-256 hash

RSA signature over hash

Stored fields:

commitmentHash

signature

logical timestamp (ts)

authorityProof

requestId

Immutability is cryptographically enforced.

Any mutation invalidates hash.

Logical Clock

Uses global Postgres sequence:

SELECT nextval('ledger_global_seq')

This guarantees:

Total ordering

Cross-case determinism

Replay stability

No reliance on system clock

Time is logical, not temporal.

Supersession Enforcement

If supersedesCommitId is provided:

The service validates:

Target exists

Same tenant

Not already superseded

Authority hierarchy valid

This prevents:

Cross-tenant override

Double supersession

Privilege escalation

Governance corruption

Canonicalization

The canonicalize() method:

Sorts object keys

Recursively serializes

Produces stable string

Two identical logical payloads always produce identical hash.

No randomness.
No field order drift.

5. Ledger Metrics

File:
ledgerMetrics.service.ts

Read-only telemetry per tenant.

Exposes:

Total commits

Lifecycle transition count

Verification events

Repair events

Supersession count

24h activity

Last commit timestamp

This is governance density telemetry.

It does NOT:

Infer lifecycle

Change state

Mutate ledger

Repair authority

When commit volume grows large:

Introduce materialized aggregates.

6. Ledger Health

LedgerService exposes:

getStatus()

Returns:

ok

latestCommitTs

Health endpoints must never expose:

private key

signature material

authority internals

Health is observability only.

Operational Directories

Ledger stores keys in:

data/keys/private.pem
data/keys/public.pem

If missing:

Keys are generated automatically.

Private key never leaves server boundary.

Public key can be exported for external verification if needed.

Governance Principles

Ledger is append-only.

Never:

Update existing commit

Delete commit

Modify hash

Modify signature

Supersession creates a new commit referencing prior one.

History is immutable.

Authority evolves through explicit supersession.

Determinism

Given identical input:

tenantId

caseId

eventType

actor

authorityProof

payload

Ledger produces identical commitmentHash.

This enables:

Replay validation

External auditing

Deterministic reconstruction

Transaction Discipline

Ledger commit must occur inside the same transaction that mutates domain state.

Never:

Commit before mutation

Commit outside transaction boundary

Wrap commit in nested transaction

Ledger causality must align with state mutation.

Otherwise replay breaks.

What This Module Is Not

It is not:

Business rule engine

Lifecycle resolver

Authorization middleware

Role-based access system

Analytics engine

It is constitutional authority memory.

Failure Philosophy

If commit validation fails:

Throw explicit error.

Do not auto-correct.

Authority failure is fatal.

Ledger integrity must never degrade silently.

Scaling Considerations

When commit volume per tenant grows large:

Partition by tenant

Add materialized metrics table

Introduce read replicas

Archive old commits to cold storage (append-only)

Never prune active ledger.

Institutional memory must remain intact.

Security Considerations

Protect private.pem with file permissions.

Never expose signature validation endpoint without strict authentication.

Monitor supersession frequency.

Alert on unusual authority escalation patterns.

Authority abuse often reveals itself in override density.

Mental Model

Ledger is constitutional law.

Domain services are legislators.
Controllers are clerks.
Projections are newspapers.

Only the constitution is immutable.

If a projection lies, the ledger corrects it.
If a service misbehaves, the ledger records it.
If authority escalates improperly, the ledger blocks it.

Truth flows from here.

Ready for the next module boundary.
